data.content:
Here's the full migration. Your code has three `Thread.Abort`-dependent patterns:

| Pattern | Location | Modern Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | `btnExport_Click` | Return a `FileContentResult` |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `btnRedirect_Click` | Return `RedirectResult` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `btnRedirect_Click` | Remove entirely |

## Migrated ASP.NET Core Controller (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // Export: return a FileResult — the framework handles headers and response completion.
    // No Response.Clear/Write/End needed; no ThreadAbortException possible.
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();
        return File(
            Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv");
    }

    // Redirect: return RedirectResult — never pass endResponse:true,
    // never catch ThreadAbortException.
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Redirect()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key changes explained

**1. `Response.End()` → return from action method**
ASP.NET Core has no `Response.End()`. You don't need to manually clear/write/flush the response. Returning `File(...)` sets `Content-Type`, `Content-Disposition`, and writes the body — all in one shot.

**2. `Response.Redirect(url, true)` → `return Redirect(url)`**
The `true` (endResponse) parameter existed solely to call `Thread.Abort` and halt execution. In ASP.NET Core, `return Redirect(...)` exits the action method naturally — no thread termination needed.

**3. `catch (ThreadAbortException)` → removed entirely**
This catch block only existed because `Response.Redirect(url, true)` threw `ThreadAbortException` as a side effect. With the return-based flow, no exception is thrown, so no catch is needed.

## Common pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| Calling `HttpContext.Response.Redirect()` and continuing execution | Unlike Framework, this **does not** stop execution. Code after it still runs. Always `return` immediately after, or use `return Redirect(...)`. |
| Leftover `ThreadAbortException` catch blocks | These become dead code that silently swallows `OperationCanceledException` if you ever refactor to catch `Exception` broadly. Remove them. |
| Writing to `Response.Body` after returning a result | ASP.NET Core throws `InvalidOperationException` if you mix manual response writing with action results. Pick one approach. |
| Not handling `?.IsAuthenticated` null safety | `User.Identity` can be `null` in ASP.NET Core if no auth middleware is configured. Use null-conditional (`?.`) access. |
| Missing `[Authorize]` attribute | Instead of manual `IsAuthenticated` checks, prefer `[Authorize]` on the action/controller and let the middleware handle redirects to login. |

## If you have long-running request work

Use `HttpContext.RequestAborted` (a `CancellationToken`) to cooperatively cancel if the client disconnects:

```csharp
[HttpPost]
public async Task<IActionResult> LongExport(CancellationToken cancellationToken)
{
    // ASP.NET Core automatically binds this to HttpContext.RequestAborted
    var data = await GenerateReportAsync(cancellationToken);
    return File(Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data), "text/csv", "report.csv");
}
```

This replaces the old pattern where `Response.End()` + `Thread.Abort` would tear down work on disconnect — now the token signals cooperatively and `OperationCanceledException` propagates cleanly.
